# Skills

Reusable procedural knowledge for AI agents working in this project.

## Structure

Each skill lives in its own directory with a `SKILL.md` file:

```
skills/
  my-skill/
    SKILL.md       # Required: name, description in frontmatter
    references/    # Optional: detail files loaded on demand
    scripts/       # Optional: executable scripts bundled with the skill
```

## SKILL.md Format

```yaml
---
name: my-skill
description: >
  Use this skill when deploying, updating, or checking status of services,
  even if the user doesn't explicitly say "deploy". Covers nginx, PM2, and
  systemd operations.
---

# My Skill

Detailed instructions for the agent.
```

## Progressive Disclosure

Skills load in three tiers to minimize token cost:

1. **Metadata** (name + description) - always in agent context. This is the trigger mechanism.
2. **SKILL.md body** - loaded only when the skill activates.
3. **references/ and scripts/** - loaded on demand from within the body.

Keep descriptions under 1024 characters. The body can be any length, but if it exceeds
500 lines, split detail into `references/` files and load them selectively.

## Writing Good Skills

**Descriptions are triggers.** The agent decides whether to use a skill based on
name + description alone. Be pushy - list the specific situations that should activate
the skill, not just what it does.

**Anti-examples prevent failures.** List the 3-5 most common mistakes the agent
makes for this task, with reasoning for why each is wrong. A model that understands
the reasoning generalizes better than one following bare prohibitions.

**Concrete tests beat abstract rules.** Instead of "the output must be high quality,"
give a mechanical test: "cover the summary with your hand and read the takeaway alone -
does it teach something useful on its own?"

**Quality self-check.** End with a 3-5 point checklist the agent verifies after
producing output but before reporting done. Target the highest error rates.

## Size Budget

| Lines | Guidance |
|-------|----------|
| < 200 | Lightweight, no concern |
| 200-500 | Every section should earn its place |
| 500+ | Split detail into `references/` files with pointers about when to read them |
